For completeness, below are the references
**The Substraction Rules:**
```
 There are six instances where subtraction is used:
I can be placed before V (5) and X (10) to make 4 and 9. 
X can be placed before L (50) and C (100) to make 40 and 90. 
C can be placed before D (500) and M (1000) to make 400 and 900.
```
**The Mappings:**
```
('I', 1)
('V', 5)
('X', 10)
('L', 50)
('C', 100)
('D', 500)
('M', 1000)
```

Examples
```
3 -> III
58- > LVIII
1994 -> MCMXCIV
```
Score (the score is not constant for some reason)
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/bef342b3-9f4d-4769-8315-5cc924e5c8ff_1649363126.5775585.jpeg)

**Follow Up**
The benefit of this method is fully extensible. If it has to support larger number over the current limit, new mappings can be added in `map` variable, even during runtime, the rest of the code remains unchanged.

For example, adding new symbols or loading them in runtime is like below:

   `itr.map.add(new String[] { "M", "", "" });`

This is the important and bonus point if asked during an interview.

```
class Solution {

	public static List<String[]> map = new ArrayList<String[]>();//public for runtime call
	static {
		map.add(new String[] { "I", "V", "X" });
		map.add(new String[] { "X", "L", "C" });
		map.add(new String[] { "C", "D", "M" });
		map.add(new String[] { "M", "", "" });
	}

	public String intToRoman(int num) {
		StringBuilder rs = new StringBuilder();
		int n = map.size();
		for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
			intToRoman(rs, num / ((int) Math.pow(10, i)) % 10, map.get(i)[0], map.get(i)[1], map.get(i)[2]);
		}
		return rs.toString();
	}

	private void intToRoman(StringBuilder sb, int num, String one, String five, String ten) {
		if (1 <= num) {
			if (num < 4) {
				sb.append(one.repeat(num));
			} else if (num < 5) { // num >= 4 && num < 5)
				sb.append(one).append(five);
			} else if (num == 5) {
				sb.append(five);
			} else if (num < 9) { // num > 5 && num < 9
				sb.append(five).append(one.repeat(num - 5));
			} else { // num >= 9 && num < 10
				sb.append(one).append(ten);
			}
		}
	}
}
```
